    "description": "<p><strong>A Mysterious Volume of Holiday Field Recordings<\/strong><br \/>\nMichael Ryan\/Ireland, France\/2014\/15 min\/UK premiere<br \/>\nThe meticulous documentation of the tactility of the seaside landscape proffers a mirror reflection of the process of ardent perception, which is implicit to filmmaking practice.<\/p>\n<p><strong>The Figures Carved into Knife by the Sap of Banana Tree (As Figuras Gravadas Na Faca Com A Seiva Das Bananeiras)<\/strong><br \/>\nJoana Pimenta\/Portugal, USA\/2014\/17 min\/UK premiere<br \/>\nA fabricated archive of memory in the form of postcards exchanged between Madeira and Mozambique. Mysterious images drift across the frame, akin to snatched snippets from long since sent letters.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Field Notes<\/strong><br \/>\nVashti Harrison\/USA, Trinidad &amp; Tobago\/2014\/18 min\/UK premiere<br \/>\nA textural oral and visual travelogue, drawing forth the superstition and spirits embedded within the cultural identity of Trinidad and Tobago.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Nan Lakou Kanaval<\/strong><br \/>\nKaveh Nabatian\/Canada, Haiti\/2014\/8 min\/UK premiere<br \/>\nA multi-sensory mapping of the riot of jostling bodies, rapturous rhythms, and collective holler channelled through Haiti's Nan Lakau Carnival.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Ottery<\/strong><br \/>\nTom Chick\/UK\/2015\/8 min\/World premiere<br \/>\nA reverberating blur of bodies and fire conjures forth representation of the potent and intoxicating Southern English folk custom of the flaming tar barrel dash.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Transition (Dakujem ti, mel&oacute;nik)<\/strong><br \/>\nBarbora Chalupov&aacute;\/Czech Republic\/2014\/16 min\/UK premiere<br \/>\nThe pursuit of deeper spiritual engagement and rejection of the ego facilitate the transition to the esoteric Prana diet, undertaken by 30-year-old soldier Michal.<\/p>",
